###### Remark 4.4.3.

1. (1)

   If X is normal and excellent, then \operatorname{\underline{K}}\_{1}(X)\simeq\mathbf{G}\_{m}(X), and by
   Proposition 4.3.11 the map (4.4.1.a) is the usual determinant
   map K^{\prime}\_{1}(X)\to\mathbf{G}\_{m}(X). In particular, when X is regular (so that
   K^{\prime}\_{1}(X)\simeq K\_{1}(X)), the group \operatorname{SK}^{\prime}\_{1}(X) identifies with the classical
   group \operatorname{SK}\_{1}(X).
